dy":"The misuse of the word palindrome for these sequences is a real pet hate of mine - they&#39;re rotationally symmetrical not palindromic!"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2550973bfc1f6c08ff29efee9a1cc7fa?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":2938,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/2938/jack-aidley","reputation":3478,"display_name":"Jack Aidley"},"score":0,"post_id":1168,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/TVDAK.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":69,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/69/rory-m","reputation":9094,"display_name":"Rory M","accept_rate":88},"edited":false,"creation_date":1358948841,"comment_id":8443,"body":"@RoryM: I have no idea why you&#39;re intepreting Larry&#39;s answer as suggesting that rotationally symmetrical - ;) - recognition sequences have to be even what he is saying is that the <i>duplication<\/i> of a single recognition module can produce a rotationally symmetrical recognition sequence and that <i>this<\/i> will lead to an even length recognition sequence."}],"down_vote_count":3,"last_activity_date":1330028830,"creation_date":1330028830,"body":"<p>Most restriction enzymes recognize palindromes, hence the recognition site of an even number of residues. Why palindromes? This allows for a vast increase in complexity (or rarity) from a DNA sequence standpoint, while requiring very little added complexity from the protein. In other words, if a protein domain recognizes 2 or 3 or 4 bp of DNA, simply adding a second copy of that domain to the peptide chain (via duplication of the DNA encoding that domain) does the trick. It is much easier to duplicate a module than to build a new or second (perhaps complimentary) module.<\/p>\n","answer_id":1168,"question_id":1167,"up_vote_count":4},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4e8d0828732c8eb54a0335e7eab1ec9f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":112,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/112/michael-kuhn","reputation":3583,"display_name":"Michael Kuhn","accept_rate":75},"score":9,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/222b478bab6d59dc5de514a87dba88cd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":389,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/389/bobthejoe","reputation":4911,"display_name":"bobthejoe","accept_rate":53},"score":1,"post_id":1207,"edited":false,"creation_date":1330326153,"comment_id":1452,"body":"I would guess that the followup question is why is this the case?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3bb465ba7c2338b41ef15a2a05306a7c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":444,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/444/gianpaolo-r","reputation":3120,"display_name":"Gianpaolo R","accept_rate":40},"score":1,"post_id":1207,"edited":false,"creation_date":1330346696,"comment_id":1454,"body":"Interesting. Is there any motif in the length 6 sites?"},{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"user560"},"score":0,"post_id":1207,"edited":false,"creation_date":1333714166,"comment_id":2191,"body":"I think you&#39;ve found the natural bias that exists for recognition sites. The distribution is symmetric for 4-8 bases, and obviously cannot get much smaller than 4 without losing a great deal of specificity and as a consequence, not being very useful. At the other extreme, the larger the stretch of DNA required, the larger the enzyme must be which is expensive, and while you gain specificity you sacrifice cutting efficiency for things like methylation and secondary structure."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1330293064,"creation_date":1330293064,"body":"<p>I think this is due to the over-representation of recognition sites with length 6:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>data&lt;-c(16, 16, 12, 12, 6, 6, 6, 6, 4, 16, 6, 6, 6, 6, 15, 15, 6, 6, 6, 6, 11, 11, 6, 6, 4, 4, 6, 6, 11, 12, 6