h diet, exercise, etc, will give you some very interesting possibilities.<\/p>\n","answer_id":1146,"question_id":1126,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1329931134},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/61200477cf8983809ec152f484750204?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":234,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/234/pierre","reputation":183,"display_name":"Pierre"},"score":2,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1330096967,"creation_date":1330010107,"body":"<p>Some other ones:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><p><strong>Are you a Singer?<\/strong> :-)  AVPR1A and SLC6A4 Polymorphisms in Choral Singers and Non-Musicians: A Gene Association Study <a href=\"http://www.plosone.org/article/info%3Adoi%2F10.1371%2Fjournal.pone.0031763\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.plosone.org/article/info%3Adoi%2F10.1371%2Fjournal.pone.0031763<\/a><\/p><\/li>\n<li><p><strong>Do you have sunbed sessions?<\/strong><\/p><\/li>\n<li><p><strong>Do you dance?<\/strong>  (via C.Dina. ) <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1239939\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1239939<\/a><\/p><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n","answer_id":1166,"question_id":1126,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1330096967}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/1126/questions-to-ask-to-a-panel-of-people-that-will-be-sequenced","last_activity_date":1330096967,"creation_date":1329846059,"answer_count":4,"title":"Questions to ask to a panel of people that will be sequenced","body":"<p>Some genes have been shown to be <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17667961\" rel=\"nofollow\">associated with left-handedness<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>Working with some clinicians, I've recommend them to ask their patients (whose genome will be sequenced) if they are \"right or left-handed\".\nIt's a simple phenotype (without any ethical issue) that will be later fun/interesting to analyze through the sequencing data outside of the main study.<\/p>\n\n<p>Do you know any other such kind of simple phenotype that we could ask to our patients ? :-)<\/p>\n","question_id":1126,"tags":["dna-sequencing","human-genetics"],"score":12,"accepted_answer_id":1128,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":468,"up_vote_count":12,"last_edit_date":1330023007},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5cff3e84bcedd40163c74d33b827ac7c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":307,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/307/lancelafontaine","reputation":3814,"display_name":"LanceLafontaine","accept_rate":47},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fdd630f72eef3790bfb4ef38d08c7f85?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":166,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/166/konrad-rudolph","reputation":3847,"display_name":"Konrad Rudolph"},"score":0,"post_id":1024,"edited":false,"creation_date":1329260913,"comment_id":1236,"body":"Can\u2019t help myself \u2026<a href=\"https://twitter.com/#!/klmr/status/167932585190752256\" rel=\"nofollow\">relevant<\/a> (but here the better word would be \u201cexplanation\u201d). <a href=\"http://blogs.discovermagazine.com/notrocketscience/2010/11/24/on-jargon-and-why-it-matters-in-science-writing/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Ed Yong thinks to, too<\/a>."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5cff3e84bcedd40163c74d33b827ac7c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":307,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/307/lancelafontaine","reputation":3814,"display_name":"LanceLafontaine","accept_rate":47},"score":0,"post_id":1024,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fdd630f72eef3790bfb4ef38d08c7f85?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":166,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/166/konrad-rudolph","reputation":3847,"display_name":"Konrad Rudolph"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1329264522,"comment_id":1238,"body":"Explanation isn&#39;t really the word I&#39;m looking for, as I do know what the terms mean individually, but not in relation to each other. I&#39;ll edit it to read &quot;distinction&quot;."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/720def7e174e03c60b8274f31da43f27?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":526,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/526/cixelyn","reputation":521,"display_name":"Cixelyn"},"score":6,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1329975663,"creation_date":1329975663,"body":"<p>If I understand the nomenclature correctly, an R plasmid is just any plasmid containing an antibiotic (<strong>R<\/strong>)esistance gene (eg. Amp, Kan, Cm, etc.). It's a bit of an outdated name from when people didn't know how exactly the plasmids conferred such resistance.<\/p>\n\n<p>An F-plasmid is any plasmid that contains the genes necessary for (<strong>F<\/strong>)ertility, eg:horizontal gene transfer via the <em>tra<\/em> operon.<\/p>\n\n<p>The two do not have to appear together -- eg: Many F plamids will contain resistance genes (along with other random chunks from the genome), but resistance doesn't always have to be part of the payload. Likewise, it is common in labs to build pure resistance vectors that lack any horizontal transfer capability in order to select for particular clones.<\/p>\n","answer_id":1161,"question_id":1024,"up_vote_count":6}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/1024/what-is-the-distinction-between-f-plasmid-and-r-plasmid","last_activity_date":1329975663,"creation_date":1329157560,"answer_count":1,"title":"What is the distinction between F' plasmid and R plasmid?","body":"<p>Is there a difference between an F' plasmid that has taken up a chromosomal gene that conveys antibiotic resistance, and an R plasmid? Is a bacterium containing an R plasmid and yet lacking an F+ plasmid capable of horizontal gene transfer by conjugation?<\/p>\n","ques