age":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/31d14b825ffd4d6b3f360a04b148c19e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":512,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/512/valentinos","reputation":31,"display_name":"Valentinos"},"score":3,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1329493044,"creation_date":1329492502,"body":"<p>Cell clumps that not dissociate with rigorous pipetting might very well be caused from free DNA in your cell suspension (i.e. if you trypsinized for too long). Free DNA attracts cells which bind altogether forming clumps.<\/p>\n\n<p>Two possible ways to get rid of these clumps:<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Centrifuge your cell suspension at 5000 rpm for 2 minutes with acceleration on (at 4) and brake (at 3) allowing the way heavier molecules to precipitate. Then aspirate ~0.5ml from the top of the suspension and transfer to a new flask. Repeat if needed.<\/li>\n<li>Use DNAse at concentrations from 20-100µg/ml (concentration resulted from personal use) as long as you will not intend to carry out DNA related experiments.<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>You can always go back and buy a fresh ampule of the cell line you want clumps free :)<\/p>\n","answer_id":1085,"question_id":279,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1329493044}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/279/how-do-you-break-up-cell-clumps-when-passaging","last_activity_date":1329493044,"creation_date":1324518936,"answer_count":3,"title":"How do you break up cell clumps when passaging?","body":"<p>I am working with HepG2 cells, and they really like to form clumps.  Pipetting up and down in TrypLE does not seem to be very effective in breaking them up.<\/p>\n","question_id":279,"tags":["cell-culture"],"score":5,"down_vote_count":1,"is_answered":true,"view_count":1818,"up_vote_count":6},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/XDA2o.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":338,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/338/j-musser","repu