6,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1329477058,"creation_date":1329477058,"body":"<p>The sense of depth is required to us to orient ourselves in a 3D world. Insects do orient themselves in the exterior 3D world, thanks to the ability to detect the plane of sunlight polarization, that is used as a navigation compass in foraging expeditions and when coming back home.<\/p>\n\n<p>You can find a good review on Current Biology (<a href=\"http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.cub.2007.05.022\">Krapp 2007<\/a>) and a <a href=\"http://courses.cit.cornell.edu/ent201/vision.html\">lecture about insect vision<\/a> from Cornell University. <\/p>\n","answer_id":1083,"question_id":1071,"up_vote_count":6}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/1071/do-insects-with-compound-eyes-have-depth-perception","last_activity_date":1329479663,"creation_date":1329445356,"answer_count":2,"title":"Do insects with compound eyes have depth perception?","body":"<p>Do insects with compound eyes have depth perception? They fly as if they do, but their eyes are so close together it seems like the image would be 2 dimensional.<\/p>\n","question_id":1071,"tags":["entomology","vision"],"score":11,"accepted_answer_id":1080,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":933,"up_vote_count":11,"last_edit_date":1329479663},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2596d9baef66702ce5302a02bd831d95?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":245,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/245/maxim-v-pavlov","reputation":277,"display_name":"Maxim V. Pavlov"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fcdaa233771f8678fc6e261bb69446c1?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":34,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/34/jonas","reputation":875,"display_name":"Jonas"},"score":12,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2596d9baef66702ce5302a02bd