's why cats will want to scratch everywhere), or if has supernumerary toes that don't normally touch the ground. Similarly, cattle that doesn't get to move will suffer from hoof overgrowth, which appears to be very uncomfortable to the animal.<\/p>\n\n<p>Consequently, if you were to use your fingernails more often for digging and scratching, you wouldn't have to trim them all the time. <\/p>\n","answer_id":330,"question_id":329,"up_vote_count":12}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/329/why-are-there-nail-growth-differences-between-humans-and-other-mammals","last_activity_date":1329474474,"creation_date":1324814862,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why are there nail growth differences  between humans and other mammals?","body":"<p>When a cat is growing, his nails are growing with him to some extent. A grown cat has a fixed nail length that is not extending.<\/p>\n\n<p>By contrast, human finger nails just keep on growing, so we have to cut them to keep an aesthetically pleasing look.<\/p>\n\n<p>Nature clearly has a mechanism to control nail growth.<\/p>\n\n<p>What is the most probable reason as to why this is not implemented in humans?<\/p>\n","question_id":329,"tags":["evolution","anatomy","human-anatomy","theoretical-biology"],"score":9,"accepted_answer_id":330,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":916,"up_vote_count":9,"last_edit_date":1329474474},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3d9515a7c0965977892f1c897bf9191d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":96,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/96/bobtheowl2","reputation":390,"display_name":"bobtheowl2","accept_rate":60},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/TVDAK.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":69,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/69/rory-m","reputation":9094,"display_name":"Rory M","accept_rate":88},"score":0,"post_id":1064,"edited":false,"creation_date":1329434621,"comment_id":1277