_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2550aa98332616362fa07d023da45d40?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":28,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/28/gergana-vandova","reputation":5081,"display_name":"Gergana Vandova","accept_rate":35},"score":3,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/28b0c2645da6a61f949db6196e52c567?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":184,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/184/thomas-ingalls","reputation":1306,"display_name":"Thomas Ingalls"},"score":0,"post_id":1076,"edited":false,"creation_date":1329460039,"comment_id":1287,"body":"The maximum rates change with the product version, by the way.  The Veriti &quot;Fast&quot;, 96-well has a ramp rate of 5 &#176;C/s while the Veriti &quot;normal&quot;, 96-well&#39;s max. sample ramp rate is 3.35 &#176;C/s.  But still, this would be a 3% ramp rate, not 5% like you found."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1329457755,"creation_date":1329457755,"body":"<p>As Thomas pointed out, there is a maximum ramp rate which you can set up on the thermocycler. Its value can go from 0% to 100%. I can then assume that a 100% ramp rate will corespond to the maximum ramp rate of 4.25°C/s for the heating block or 5°C/s for the sample. which means that a ramp rate of ~2.4%. Subsequently, I set up my reaction at a 2% ramp rate, as I started a timer at the time the ramp cycle started. To my surprise, the temperature was cooling down too slowly. Thus, I empirically found out that a ramp rate of 5% corresponds to ~0.1°C/s cooling speed. <\/p>\n\n<p>I wished there was more precise way to calculate it. Perhaps the slope of the line changed at different temperature intervals. It would be great if I can talk to the AB people so that they could justify my finding.<\/p>\n","answer_id":1076,"question_id":1070,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/1070/how-to-set-up-a-slow-