ing which the fly is \"blind.\"<\/p>\n\n<p>The actual turn begins with the generation of a torque, which starts the fly turning. Shortly thereafter, the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haltere\">halteres<\/a> sense this change and a counter-torque is produces, which stops the turn.<\/p>\n\n<p>Rather than random turns, <em>Drosophila<\/em> are turning away from visual expansion as they near objects. So as they move closer to an object, it expands in their visual field, and they turn away from it.<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/CxHuC.jpg\" alt=\"Schematic of fruit fly turning\"><\/p>\n","answer_id":758,"question_id":753,"up_vote_count":23},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/49e94b363348f897f337a5bce2beec20?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":68,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/68/marta-cz-c","reputation":1717,"display_name":"Marta Cz-C","accept_rate":50},"score":8,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1327520981,"creation_date":1327494892,"body":"<p>Quick search - Some articles that may interest you:<\/p>\n\n<p>1) Random walk model of insect movements\n<br>\n<a href=\"http://www.springerlink.com/content/m525270k7647u074/\">Kareiva P. M., Shigesada N. (1983). Analyzing insect movement as a correlated random walk. Oecologia 56(2-3) 234-238<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>2) Artificial life model of flying insects and its comparison to real insects navigation strategies.\n<br>\n<a href=\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0960982201004183\">Dale K., Collett T. C. (2001). Using artificial evolution and selection to model insect navigation. Current Biology 11(17) 1305\u20131316<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>3) The last one is not about insects, but it's a trial to practical usage of the mathematical analisys of invertebrate movements.\n<br>\n<a href=\"http://dx.doi.org/10.1002/tox.10077\">Shimizu N. et al. (2002). Fractal analysis of Daphnia motion for acute toxicity bioassay. Environmental Toxicology 17(5) 441\u2013448<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":807,"question_id":753,"up_vote_count":8,"last_edit_date":1327520981}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/753/what-are-the-trajectories-of-flying-insects","last_activity_date":1329403766,"creation_date":1327257283,"answer_count":2,"title":"What are the trajectories of flying insects?","body":"<p>Many flying insects tend to have very jagged trajectories. For moves of a fruit fly looks like a <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_walk\">random walk<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>Is there any research on the properties of trajectories (e.g. their fractal dimension or mathematical models producing similar behaviour)?<\/p>\n\n<p>Besides the path of a single insect, I am also interested in the interaction of a small number of insects (e.g. 2 or 3).<\/p>\n\n<p>I am aware of the research in flocking and swarming (e.g. Tamas Vicsek, Anna Zafiris, <a href=\"http://arxiv.org/abs/1010.5017\">Collective motion<\/a> 2010) and of techniques of obtaining such trajectories (e.g. Danping Zou, Yan Qiu Chen, <a href=\"http://dx.doi.org/10.1109/ICCVW.2009.5457649\">Acquiring 3D motion trajectories of large numbers of swarming animals<\/a> or an <a href=\"http://users.soe.ucsc.edu/~manazhao/files/iccv09_voec.pdf\">open access pdf<\/a>, 2009). However, I haven't found within them an answer to my particular question.<\/p>\n","question_id":753,"tags":["zoology","biophysics","mathematical-models","collective-behaviour","entomology"],"score":28,"accepted_answer_id":807,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":829,"up_vote_count":28,"last_edit_date":1329403766},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/10468219739fa16d239f6370c2db9c4c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":464,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/464/supuhstar","reputation":176,"display_name":"Supuhstar"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/10468219739fa16d239f6370c