t it somewhere, you can deduce this solution. So nutrition and external \"hatching\" or development outside of female is the key here.<\/p>\n\n<p>The overall answer to the question:\n<strong>The organism must have a yolk sac, since it has yolk<\/strong>.<\/p>\n\n<p>The second question seems to be an idealized one.\nWithout blastocoele but with yolk-sac suggests me that the blastocoel has developed already to yolk-sac. If that is the case, then I would call the thing gastrula, since for instance some species' ectoderm develops into yolk-sac. I assume that the question refers with \"yolk-sac\" to complete yolk-sac, not to the developing one during gastrulation.<\/p>\n\n<p>If it is about developing yolk-sac, I would say that the cell is still blastula but is developing to gastrula. The yolk sac is not ready until gastrulation is complete.<\/p>\n","answer_id":999,"question_id":948,"up_vote_count":0,"last_edit_date":1329035068}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/948/does-amphibian-embryos-blastocoel-become-a-primitive-yolk-sac-without-yolk","last_activity_date":1329035068,"creation_date":1328649352,"answer_count":1,"title":"Does Amphibian embryo's blastocoel become a primitive yolk sac without yolk?","body":"<p>The mammalian blastocoel becomes yolk sac without yolk according to my professor. I have not found any evidence that such a thing happens in amphibians like frog.<\/p>\n\n<p>I need to be able to compare and contrast cleavage and formation of blastula in amphibians and in humans.\nMy thoughts raised another question.\nMy friend says that blastula exists only when blastocoel exists.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>2. Is the thing without blastocoel but with yolk sac the blastula?<\/strong><\/p>\n","question_id":948,"tags":["physiology","homework","development"],"score":4,"accepted_answer_id":999,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":574,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1328670024},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/49d0d23