 that it just a maturation step, since there will only be one ovum, while 4 male spermatozoa where the differentiation makes sense. I will fix it. Please, reply if I am wrong."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1328981842,"creation_date":1328981842,"body":"<p>I seem to now understand the sentence. I read the clause in other words:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>During meiosis I, the sex chromosomes of the gametogonia separate in\n  anaphase I and II and become eventually different sperm or egg cells\n  after cell differentiation and maturation: male spermiogenesis and\n  female maturation into ovum.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Female thing does not seem to have a special name for the maturation thing.\nFemale does not seem to have differentiation part at the last part similarly as male, since only one ovum is formed after the sequence of events. \nSex chromosomes refer to your parents genotypes. [jg89]<\/p>\n\n<p>Problem seems to be solved now.<\/p>\n\n<p>I would not personally use the word \"enter\" in a such sequence. It is a shortcut. Better would be \"enter eventually\" or \"enter after a sequence of events\". I prefer explicity instead of implicity.<\/p>\n","answer_id":995,"question_id":953,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/953/what-does-entering-of-sex-chromosomes-to-gametes-mean-during-meiosis-i","last_activity_date":1328981842,"creation_date":1328730015,"answer_count":1,"title":"What does entering of sex chromosomes to gametes mean during meiosis I?","body":"<p>I am reading <a href=\"http://wiki.answers.com/Q/What_is_the_difference_between_male_meiosis_and_female_meiosis_for_humans\" rel=\"nofollow\">one answer about meiosis<\/a>:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>During meiosis I, the sex chromosomes separate and enter different\n  sperm or egg cells (gametes).<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>I assume that sex chromosomes refer here to homologous chromosomes that experience crossing-over after meiosis that is exchange of genetical information.<\/p>\n\n<p>Meiosis I refers here to female meiosis I and to male meiosis I. \nIn both cases, homologous chromosomes separate resulting in haploid cells after meiosis I.\n<em>These homologous chromosomes enter sperm or egg cells<\/em> according to the writer, which I cannot understand, since the given chromosomes, now sister chromatids after meiosis I, do not enter physically anything, they just divide into haploid cells, gametes, after meiosis II.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>What is the meaning of the word \"enter\" in the given sentence?<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>I am confused by the word \"enter\".\nI am assuming that the word refers to enter something physically which is not the case in my opinion here.<\/p>\n","question_id":953,"tags":["homework","meiosis"],"score":2,"accepted_answer_id":995,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":728,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1328781277},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/TVDAK.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":69,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/69/rory-m","reputation":9094,"display_name":"Rory M","accept_rate":88},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/33af7b8879cdcdfdb5edb7b1f265fd9c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":430,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/430/richard-smith-unna","reputation":7703,"display_name":"Richard Smith-Unna","accept_rate":90},"score":1,"post_id":982,"edited":false,"creation_date":1328958470,"comment_id":1169,"body":"As a side question, how are you doing all this lab work as an A-level student? V. impressive!"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/TVDAK.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":69,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/69/rory-m","reputation":9094,"display_name":"Rory M","accept_rate":88},"score":0,"post_id":982,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/33af7b8879cdcdfdb5edb7b1f265fd9c?s=128&d