ize a human with <em>Clostridium difficile<\/em>. There's no human challenge studies, and since it's not a foodborne pathogen, little we can get from outbreak data.<\/p>\n\n<p>Which leaves me looking at animal models, to at least get the <em>shape<\/em> of the probability of infection based on a given dose. But the papers on hamsters makes it appear that they're infected rather easily, and that this infection is particularly severe.<\/p>\n\n<p>Is there another animal model that more closely mimics the infection dynamics of <em>C. difficile<\/em> in humans?<\/p>\n","question_id":177,"tags":["microbiology","epidemiology"],"score":14,"accepted_answer_id":969,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":159,"up_vote_count":14},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/75ac58e3e0106650994b315a6ad4c525?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":103,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/103/inquilinekea","reputation":1084,"display_name":"InquilineKea","accept_rate":52},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4b21f13b2388dab1c90910e64b84e7a9?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":452,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/452/tim-smith","reputation":304,"display_name":"Tim Smith"},"score":3,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1328521437,"creation_date":1328419909,"body":"<p>Looking at the articles referenced in the Wikipedia article, there's probably no direct physiological link between senescence and beta-galactosides. <a href=\"http://dx.doi.org/10.1111/j.1474-9726.2006.00199.x\" rel=\"nofollow\">Lee et al (2006)<\/a> and others before them have shown that the \"hypothetical\" protein is just regular lysosomal beta-galactosidase, which is present in higher concentrations in aging and stressed cells because the number of lysosomes increase under those conditions. There's a collection of references in the Discussion section of the Lee paper that delves deeper into the aging-lysosome connection.<\/p>\n\n<p>I'm well out of my depth by this point, but if I were going to take a wild guess I'd suggest that lysosomal upregulation could be part of a stress response involving autophagy (i.e. the cell breaking down and recycling intracellular materials to meet critical demands), though I don't know the specific connection to aging. As far as beta-galactosides go: if you have any hanging around, you get to eat them, is all, I bet. I bet the references in Lee would tell you if I'm on track or not.<\/p>\n","answer_id":915,"question_id":881,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1328521437}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/881/why-are-beta-galactosidase-proteins-overexpressed-in-senescent-cells","last_activity_date":1328521437,"creation_date":1328159371,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why are beta-galactosidase proteins overexpressed in senescent cells?","body":"<p><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SA-beta-gal\">Wikipedia<\/a> explains that it's a hypothetical hydrolase enzyme that catalyzes the hydrolysis of β-galactosides into monosaccharides only in senescent cells.<\/p>\n\n<p>I'm just wondering - what causes it to be overexpressed in senescent cells - to the point that it often becomes a biomarker of senescence? And what exactly happens to the particular cell when you catalyze the hydrolysis of more β-galactosides (like lactose) into monosaccharides? <\/p>\n","question_id":881,"tags":["senescence"],"score":6,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":535,"up_vote_count":6},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/2jNxG.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":368,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/368/ultimate-gobblement","reputation":827,"display_name":"Ultimate Gobblement","accept_rate":86},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/49e94b363348f897f337a5bce2beec20?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":68,"li